				\begin{document}$$ \frac{|\mathbf{j}|}{\vert \frac{c}{4\pi}\nabla\times\mathbf{B}\vert }\sim \frac{1}{\varGamma^2}. $$\end{document} Clearly, since the pulsar wind is believed to have Γ∼100–200 already at its base, a displacement current cannot be neglected, and in fact dominates over the charge current in the equatorial wind. This turns out to be important since a displacement current has a different way of dissipating (i.e. ‘Co-moving Poynting Flux Acceleration’) than the charge current.

